		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33164989"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>NavyCherub said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>how would you define melodrama?<!--quote--></div><br />
Let's begin by dispelling the most common misconception:&quot;Melodramatic&quot; does not mean &quot;sad.&quot;<br />
<br />
By the book, it's defined as &quot;exaggerated and emotional or sentimental; sensational or sensationalized; overdramatic.&quot;  In classic melodrama, each character fills a singular role and is defined by a single emotional state.  This <em>can</em> mean having a character who is always sad and morose, but a character who is always gallant and chivalrous is just as melodramatic as a character who is always melancholy.<br />
<br />
In this way, melodrama is inherently limiting.  Most character arcs are built on contrasting emotional states.  Outside of melodrama, we may see a character who is happy in one scene and morose in another, and by observing the character in different emotional states we learn more about them.  Or maybe we see a cowardly sniveling character evolve into one who is heroic and courageous over the course of the story.  In melodrama, you can't (by definition) do this.  At most, you can have characters explore different points upon a single heroic continuum.  For example, in melodrama, you can't have a character evolve from &quot;cowardly&quot; to &quot;courageous.&quot;  But you can have them evolve from &quot;pretty courageous&quot; to &quot;extremely courageous.&quot;  Melodrama  is incapable of doing many of the things that are constructive in effective storytelling.<br />
<br />
On the other hand, there are some strengths inherent to melodrama as well.<br />
<br />
One of the things that we as viewers love is when characters behave &quot;in character.&quot;  When Jonathan Joestar behaves in a manner which is stupid but brave and heroic, we cheer because <em>that's so totally JoJo</em>.  It's in his nature to cast aside logic and be courageous, and as a result it's fairly easy for our expectations to be met.  On the other hand, we do like to see characters evolve; it's rewarding to see a shrinking violet muster up courage and become the hero.  But if this change occurs too rapidly and the changes in their character aren't properly built up, you end up with characters that behave in uncharacteristic manner.<br />
<br />
There are also limitations to character progression.  Having a character with an arc where they overcome a character flaw and become a better person is rewarding when the narrative can be built around this.  But this doesn't work in the context of lengthier narratives.  All long-running shounen series are all incredibly melodramatic (in the sense of having characters that are defined by a single trait and characteristic), and this is to their benefit.  If you have characters that are constantly growing and changing over the course of hundreds of chapters or episodes, it's very easy for them to turn into elastic figures that are constantly being reformed and remade to the point of being unrecognizable.  Characters only have so much room for growth, and if you stretch them beyond that limit it begins to feel unrealistic.  Melodrama is a staple of the shounen jump battle manga for precisely this reason: have every character operate along a single axis, and you never have to worry about them acting &quot;out of character.&quot;  Maybe we get a big character building once every hundred episodes, but on a week-by-week basis, the characters remain mostly the same.<br />
<br />
I think one of the reasons that many people &quot;look down&quot; on melodrama is that we (for the most part) like our characters to be relatable.  We want them to feel like real people.  And real people aren't melodramatic: every person being experiences a full range of human emotion, and that's something that you can't achieve within the context of a melodrama.  But not every story needs to adhere to this.  There's something to be said for larger-than-life characters, like the impossibly clever Jimmy Kudo or the phenomenally heroic Kenshiro.  We don't look at a story like Detective Conan or Fist of the North Star looking for realism.  In large part, the melodrama of their stories is what draws us to them.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
