		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33169305">Kuiper, isn't your definition of meledrama a bit limiting and (forgive me) misleading? Melodrama is by definition exaggerated drama (as you pretty much stated yourself), and while often accompanied by rigid characters, does not inherently entail them. Character development can even effectively be used to create melodrama, so I can't really follow your line of thought.<br />
<br />
I see two main problems with melodrama, the first being the unrealistic events and character behaviors that usually follow it. The storyline is manipulated from its natural progression into one which brings out most emotions in viewers, and characters react in manners so as to further dramatize it. Interesting to note, however, is that most contemporary anime already suffer from these problems. Unlikely events occur all over the place, and exaggerated character behaviors with fittingly warped facial complexions can really be seen as a staple of anime in general. Are (almost) all anime melodramas?<br />
<br />
The second problem is the discrepancy between actual events and their presentation. A certain scene may not be very powerful in itself, but it may be illustrated or scored in overly dramatic ways so as to appear more emotional than it actually is. Tokyo Ghoul is the first example I can think of for this, since it's currently airing. It grabs every opportunity to emphasize just how DARK and VISCERAL its atmosphere is, and ends up cringe worthy as result. Mushishi is opposite to this; while the music and sound is a quintessential component of its experience, it also knows that silence and subtlety is often more powerful than hollow melodrama. <br />
<br />
This leads to a loaded question though: is background music and other similar stylistic elements inherently <em>fake</em>? Is it used because fiction cannot create genuine feelings through writing alone and needs to employ help from other factors which work subconsciously?</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
