		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33174209">So, since I brought the topic up, I feel obliged to say something about this.<br />
<br />
I went with melodrama as a topic because of a currently airing show: Hanayamata. Seeing people call it melodramatic is somewhat of a stark contrast from other shows which are also known for melodrama: the presentation of drama in Hanayamata is different from, say, Anohana. So to answer the first question, I feel like the question of &quot;what's common between the two shows&quot; has to be answered. <br />
<br />
As pointed out by Kuiper and superzarop, melodrama is commonly defined through exaggeration. Both Hanayamata and Anohana have moments where exaggeration is used to give impact to the audience. But beyond that, I don't find anything else in common between them because the exaggeration is used in different ways: I think Anohana's melodrama was a deliberate attempt to make the audience cry, while Hanayamata doesn't really go for a specific emotion; the character drama just happens to be exaggerated because that's how the characters really act in the context of the show. (I hope that made sense)<br />
<br />
Therefore, my stand is that the effect of melodrama depends on how it's used. Melodrama is just one of many storytelling tools, and there's many different ways to use the character exaggeration brought about by using it.<br />
<br />
<!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>superzarop said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><br />
This leads to a loaded question though: is background music and other similar stylistic elements inherently <em>fake</em>? Is it used because fiction cannot create genuine feelings through writing alone and needs to employ help from other factors which work subconsciously?<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
This question doesn't work when discussing a medium as dynamic as anime, or even film. Anime and film do not solely rely on its script or its storyboard to tell a story. Unlike books, where you just have the text and how it's presented, visual medium relies on a combination of music, animation/choreography, (voice) acting, and the script and storyboard to bring about a desired effect on the viewer. Saying that stylistic elements other than the script is fake is implying that the medium itself is inherently fake because it <em>relies</em> on the additional elements to work.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><!--link--><a href="http://oneofepisodes.wordpress.com" rel="nofollow"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.imgur.com/ETFALpg.jpg" /></a></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
