		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33181515"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>iSuckAtWriting said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>superzarop said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>deepbluejeer said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><br />
This question doesn't work when discussing a medium as dynamic as anime, or even film. Anime and film do not solely rely on its script or its storyboard to tell a story. Unlike books, where you just have the text and how it's presented, visual medium relies on a combination of music, animation/choreography, (voice) acting, and the script and storyboard to bring about a desired effect on the viewer. Saying that stylistic elements other than the script is fake is implying that the medium itself is inherently fake because it relies on the additional elements to work.<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
The main issue still stands in that background music obviously does not exist in any said fictional universe, unlike script and choreography and whatnot. Usage of music is fundamentally a deviation from realism, akin to the numerous artistic or literary movements which emphasize elements such as emotion or perception over authenticity. I'm not claiming that it is inherently negative; and more questioning its usage in realistic works.<br />
<br />
This ties in with the original question of the thread. Etymologically speaking, melodrama is simply a combination of melody and drama. This makes sense, because any piece of appropriate music will augment the dramatic tension of a scene, and in other words, exaggerate its feelings. If melodrama can be accused of being overblown and fake, any fiction which makes use of BGM is to an extent melodramatic.<!--quote--></div><br />
But then, if using music deviates from any realism, and realism is what you're looking for, why bother with any audiovisual medium to begin with instead of reading a book? LoGH and Baccano! have quite the soundtrack on them, and melodramatic is the <em>last</em> thing I've heard anyone call them. Most of the time I see <em>melodramatic</em> used as a negative descriptor anyway.<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
Well, there's lots to distinguish between the audiovisual from other mediums, such as body language, speech, and actual visuals. Even within the realistic genre, literature and film differ drastically in what they can depict, though we digress.<br />
<br />
The reason you don't hear people call LoGH or Baccano melodrama is probably because<br />
1: they are not the stereotypical tear-jerker pieces commonly associated with melodrama<br />
2: they are good works, and melodrama is usually used pejoratively.<br />
<br />
It seems like people are assigning an inherent negative connotation to the word. I'm just trying to question the dichotomy between melodrama and &quot;proper&quot; drama, since it is my view that most films are melodramatic to an extent.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
