		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser33192773" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><strong>Kuiper</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/331692.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: May 2010<br>
		  Posts: 74
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33192773"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>superzarop said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>Kuiper, isn't your definition of meledrama a bit limiting and (forgive me) misleading? Melodrama is by definition exaggerated drama (as you pretty much stated yourself), and while often accompanied by rigid characters, does not inherently entail them.<!--quote--></div><br />
I'm not entirely sure what you mean by this, but just to ensure that what I said is being understood:<br />
<!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>I said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>By the book, <strong>it's defined</strong> as &quot;exaggerated and emotional or sentimental; sensational or sensationalized; overdramatic.&quot; <strong>In classic melodrama</strong>, each character fills a singular role and is defined by a single emotional state.<!--quote--></div><br />
The first sentence provides a definition, and the second sentence remarks on characteristics of classic melodrama.  I think it's fair to evaluate subjects for melodrama based on how closely they emulate the form of classic melodrama in addition to considering the most literal definition of melodrama.<br />
<br />
On that note, I'd say that Baccano deviates from classic melodrama by having characters that have some nuance to them.  (Or at the very least, have multiple attributes that are sometimes in conflict with one another.)  For example, Jacuzzi is portrayed as a sniveling wuss prone to frequent bouts of crying, but he also has moments of courage and initiative.  (Or as the episode title puts it, &quot;Jacuzzi Splot Cries, Gets Scared and Musters Reckless Valor.&quot;)<br />
<br />
Claire Stanfield is also an interesting character. His happy-go-lucky demeanor in public seems at odds with his fits of violence during which he mercilessly mutilates the bodies of his victims.  The actions of violent killers tend to be unsympathetic, but Claire targets &quot;bad guys&quot; (people who are threatening the safety of the other train's passengers).  Clearly, Benjamin isn't a good person; both Claire and the audience are well aware of that.  But does that justify torturing him, inflicting pain solely for the sake of inflicting pain?  In classic melodrama you tend to see heroes that are 100% sympathetic paired against villains that are 0% sympathetic.  (Jonathan Joestar versus Dio Brando is a good example of this.)  While Claire isn't exactly a villain, it's difficult to call him a hero.  It's not always clear how we're supposed to feel about his actions.  And for that reason, Baccano seems pretty far from the idea of a classic melodrama.<br />
<br />
Even Ladd Russo is at odds with our melodramatic model.  In melodrama, we're primed to love the hero and hate the villain.  But Ladd Russo is (in my book) a pretty likable character.  Heck, even Dallas (who in the fiction of the Baccano universe is almost uniformly reviled) is a pretty fun character.  Pretty much the only character who is 100% unlikable is Szilard Quates, and he's actually a relatively small part of the drama in Baccano (playing no part in the events on the train in 1931).<br />
<br />
Apart from those few examples, Baccano is thematically segregated from classic melodrama in its framing.  In the first episode, the vice president and his assistant Carol speculate on who might be the &quot;main character&quot; of our story.   Baccano's lack of a clear protagonist is an obvious deviation from classic melodrama.  Fundamentally, melodrama is a form that deals with absolutes.  In Baccano, no one is clearly the main character, no one is absolutely virtuous (&quot;good guy&quot; Jacuzzi is a bootlegger who orders hits on people and &quot;good guy&quot; Firo is deeply entwined in an Italian crime syndicate).</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
